The Met Orchestra, J. S. Bach Festival, Juneteenth Celebration, Trio Fadolín, Kiki Valera, Create Your Own Series, Carnegie Hall Tours

This Thursday, Yannick Nézet-Séguin conducts The Met Orchestra and Chorus in a choral masterpiece by Brahms. On Friday and Saturday, we present free concerts in Times Square and Denny Farrell Riverbank State Park. 

Plus, experience the Orchestra of St. Luke’s Bach Festival, tour the Hall, see Bernstein conduct Mahler on Carnegie Hall+, and create your own concert series for maximum flexibility and savings throughout the upcoming 2023–2024 season.

Upcoming Events

Yannick Nézet-Séguin, Lisette Oropesa, Quinn Kelsey

Thursday, June 15 at 8 PM
Stern Auditorium / Perelman Stage

The Met Orchestra

Yannick Nézet-Séguin, Music Director and Conductor
Lisette Oropesa, Soprano
Quinn Kelsey, Baritone
The Met Chorus
Donald Palumbo, Chorus Master

The Met Orchestra and Chorus perform Brahms’s grandest creation, a masterpiece of the choral repertory: his Ein deutsches Requiem. They also perform a New York premiere by Luis Ernesto Peña Laguna.

Get Tickets

This concert is made possible, in part, by an endowment fund for choral music established by S. Donald Sussman in memory of Judith Arron and Robert Shaw.

Trio Fadolín

Friday, June 16 at 5 PM
Times Square | Manhattan

Carnegie Hall Citywide

Trio Fadolín

Free Event

The newly formed Trio Fadolín boasts a unique sonority, bringing together violin, cello, and the recently unveiled fadolín: a six-string violin with low C and F strings. No other ensemble has ever given the fadolín an integral role in an acoustic chamber music setting.

Learn More

Lead support for Carnegie Hall Citywide is provided by the Howard Gilman Foundation and the Hearst Foundations.

Kiki Valera y Su Son Cubano

Saturday, June 17 at 5 PM
Denny Farrell Riverbank State Park | Manhattan

Carnegie Hall Citywide

Kiki Valera y su Son Cubano

Free Event

Kiki Valera is one of Cuba’s foremost cuatro-guitar virtuosos and a fourth-generation member of La Familia Valera Miranda, renowned for more than a century as pioneers of Eastern Cuba’s son tradition. His ensemble features several of Latin America’s best expatriate musicians.

Learn More

Lead support for Carnegie Hall Citywide is provided by the Howard Gilman Foundation and the Hearst Foundations.

Monday, June 19 at 7 PM
Stern Auditorium / Perelman Stage

Healing of the Nations Institute of the Samuel DeWitt Proctor Conference in association with Carnegie Hall Presents

Juneteenth Celebration

All American Freedom Day: Renewing Passion for Freedom and Democracy

Juneteenth honors the beginning of our nation’s true independence—the freedom for all members of the reunited nation after the American Civil War. Join host Rev. Dr. James A. Forbes Jr., notable honorees, distinguished speakers, and a wide array of renowned artists for this national celebration of Black culture.

2023–2024 Season

The option to create your own concert series for the upcoming season is now open to all audiences!

From more than 140 unique performances from which to choose, simply select any four (or more) to lock in a discount of up to 15%, pick your own seats, save on convenience fees, and unlock benefits like unlimited no-fee ticket exchanges. Highlights include Yunchan Lim, Lea Michele, Sir András Schiff, Kronos Quartet’s 50th Anniversary Celebration, and much more.

Leonard Bernstein

Just Added: Bernstein Conducts Mahler’s 10th

Recommended on Carnegie Hall+

Leonard Bernstein was one of the foremost Mahler interpreters, and his iconic Mahler symphony cycle—featuring the Vienna Philharmonic, London Symphony Orchestra, and Israel Philharmonic Orchestra—is available exclusively on Carnegie Hall+!

This past week, the channel added a riveting performance of the Adagio from Mahler’s never-completed 10th Symphony.

Watch Trailer

Yannick Nézet-Séguin and The Met Orchestra

Five Things to Know about The Met Orchestra

From its first performance at Carnegie Hall in 1918 to the modern-day ensemble passionately led by Yannick Nézet-Séguin, The Met Orchestra remains a unique cultural and musical force. Enjoy our article about the storied ensemble in anticipation of its final performances of the 2022–2023 season.
